correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nA sequence is special if it consists of a positive number of 0s, followed by a positive number of 1s, then a positive number of 2s.\n\nFor example, [0,1,2] and [0,0,1,1,1,2] are special.\nIn contrast, [2,1,0], [1], and [0,1,2,0] are not special.\n\nGiven an array nums (consisting of only integers 0, 1, and 2), return the number of different subsequences that are special. Since the answer may be very large, return it modulo 109 + 7.\nA subsequence of an array is a sequence that can be derived from the array by deleting some or no elements without changing the order of the remaining elements. Two subsequences are different if the set of indices chosen are different.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [0,1,2,2]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The special subsequences are bolded [0,1,2,2], [0,1,2,2], and [0,1,2,2].\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [2,2,0,0]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: There are no special subsequences in [2,2,0,0].\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [0,1,2,0,1,2]\nOutput: 7\nExplanation: The special subsequences are bolded:\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n- [0,1,2,0,1,2]\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n0 <= nums[i] <= 2\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def countSpecialSubsequences(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve the problem of counting special subsequences in the given array `nums`, we can use dynamic programming. The idea is to maintain counters for the number of valid subsequences ending in `0`, `1`, and `2` as we iterate through the array.\n\nHere's the step-by-step approach:\n\n1. Initialize three variables `end0`, `end1`, and `end2` to count the number of special subsequences ending in `0`, `1`, and `2`, respectively.\n2. Iterate through each number in the array `nums`.\n3. For each number:\n   - If the number is `0`, it can either extend an existing subsequence ending in `0` or start a new subsequence. So, we update `end0` as `2 * end0 + 1` (the existing subsequences ending in `0` can either include this `0` or not, plus the new subsequence starting with this `0`).\n   - If the number is `1`, it can extend any subsequence ending in `0` or `1`. So, we update `end1` as `2 * end1 + end0` (the existing subsequences ending in `1` can either include this `1` or not, plus the subsequences ending in `0` can now be extended by this `1`).\n   - If the number is `2`, it can extend any subsequence ending in `1` or `2`. So, we update `end2` as `2 * end2 + end1` (the existing subsequences ending in `2` can either include this `2` or not, plus the subsequences ending in `1` can now be extended by this `2`).\n4. The final result will be stored in `end2`, which represents the number of special subsequences ending in `2`.\n\nHere is the implementation of the above approach:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countSpecialSubsequences(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        MOD = 10**9 + 7\n        end0, end1, end2 = 0, 0, 0\n        \n        for num in nums:\n            if num == 0:\n                end0 = (2 * end0 + 1) % MOD\n            elif num == 1:\n                end1 = (2 * end1 + end0) % MOD\n            elif num == 2:\n                end2 = (2 * end2 + end1) % MOD\n        \n        return end2\n```\n\nThis solution efficiently counts the number of special subsequences in `O(n)` time complexity, where `n` is the length of the array, and uses `O(1)` space complexity. The result is returned modulo \\(10^9 + 7\\) as required.", "estimated_date": 1627776000000}